	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />There is much controversy over such topics... It is generally agreed that NESASM is limited in lots of ways, but it is good for starting out because it's easy to set up a file to code right away. The most commonly used assembler around here is CC65 (CA65? I don't know the difference), I think, but I don't know too much about it. I use WLA-DX, but there are some things that I find annoying about it like having to put a ".w" after every "ldy 16-bit address". WLA is good, and it has lots of features, but I don't know, CC65 may have them + more.

		

